{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01XCks9Rh4AR4crYMswPqDZD","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→FROM maven:3.9.12-ibm-semeru-21-noble\n     2→\n     3→USER root\n     4→# install uv\n     5→RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends curl python3-venv python3-full     && curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh\n     6→\n     7→ENV PATH=\"/root/.local/bin:$PATH\"\n     8→\n     9→# Shared browsers path so Chromium is cached once\n    10→ENV PLAYWRIGHT_BROWSERS_PATH=/ms-playwright\n    11→RUN mkdir -p /ms-playwright && chmod 755 /ms-playwright\n    12→\n    13→# create venv and install\n    14→RUN uv venv /opt/venv     && uv pip install --python /opt/venv/bin/python playwright==1.47.0 pytest\n    15→\n    16→ENV PATH=\"/opt/venv/bin:$PATH\"\n    17→RUN playwright install --with-deps chromium\n    18→\n    19→# Set working directory\n    20→WORKDIR /app\n    21→\n    22→# Copy all the assets\n    23→COPY . .\n    24→\n    25→RUN if [ -f smoke.py ]; then chmod +x smoke.py; fi\n    26→\n    27→CMD sh -c \"mvn clean install -DskipTests && mvn spring-boot:run -pl roster-boot\"\n    28→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_014JA1AqSZqWp3F4zxGr9ToZ","session_id":"9366d3a9-49bd-4899-a76f-da6890618a7b","uuid":"96a30fab-9dc4-4543-aa56-2ef92ee54623"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_014JA1AqSZqWp3F4zxGr9ToZ","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I've systematically explored the codebase and retrieved the key files you requested. Here's a summary:\n\nProject Structure:\n- Multi-module Maven project with two modules: roster-boot and roster-common\n- Spring Boot application with Jakarta EE integration\n- Uses H2 in-memory database\n- Includes entities for League, Player, Team\n- Repositories and controllers for roster management\n\nKey Observations:\n1. Build Files: \n   - Root pom.xml is a parent POM for two modules\n   - Uses Spring Boot 3.1.0 \n   - Java 17 as the target version\n   - H2 database for runtime\n   - Uses JoinFaces for PrimeFaces integration\n\n2. Configuration:\n   - application.properties in roster-boot\n   - Uses H2 in-memory database\n   - Hibernate DDL auto-update enabled\n   - SQL logging enabled\n   - Server runs on port 8080\n\n3. Dockerfile:\n   - Based on maven:3.9.12-ibm-semeru-21-noble image\n   - Installs Python, uv, Playwright\n   - Copies project files\n   - Builds project with Maven and runs Spring Boot application\n\n4. Project Modules:\n   - roster-common: Shared utilities and common classes\n   - roster-boot: Main Spring Boot application with entities, repositories, controllers\n\n5. Test Files:\n   - Integration tests for request-related functionality\n   - Unit tests for RequestBean\n\nWould you like me to provide the full contents of all Java source files? The codebase seems to be a Spring Boot tutorial/example project for managing sports team rosters with Jakarta EE annotations."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9366d3a9-49bd-4899-a76f-da6890618a7b","uuid":"46541fe9-0a75-4f5a-96b7-0ed9a721204d"}
